Raw dev notes -- The Hub Gets Smarter (and Stabler)

Okay, so the Personal Information Hub. This thing is my brain's external hard drive, basically. It's a system I've built to ingest all sorts of information – emails, articles, newsletters – process it with AI, and then give me digestible summaries or let me query it. The goal is to cut through the noise and make sure I'm actually *learning* from the firehose of info I consume daily.

This past sprint, or whatever you want to call this period of intense hacking, was a wild ride. A huge chunk of it was dedicated to overhauling the newsletter digest pipeline. I finally separated it completely from the general AI digest, giving it its own prompt, schedule, and forwarding logic. This was critical because the general digest was getting swamped. I also enforced source labeling (TAAFT, Medium, GenAI PM) on every item, which is a huge win for context. And after realizing Gemini was only seeing truncated articles, I built a whole re-embedding pipeline for Medium articles, pulling the full content and rebuilding the title-URL map from Gmail. That was a beast. I also fixed a bunch of digest-related bugs, like ensuring catch-up logic worked correctly and preventing the newsletter digest from overwriting the AI digest (that one triggered a watchdog escalation, oops).

Beyond the digests, I added a cool new `/ask` command to my WhatsApp integration, letting me query the system directly with conversation persistence. This feels like a big step towards making the hub truly interactive. I also cleaned up a bunch of old scripts and exports, which always feels good.

But man, it wasn't all smooth sailing. The Medium truncation issue was a real "facepalm" moment – all this AI processing, and it was working with incomplete data! Debugging the triple forwarding bug was annoying; just a classic logic error where the "forwarded" marker wasn't being set correctly. Then there was the absolute nightmare of the BSODs. My machine kept crashing, and it turned out to be a `storport.sys` NVMe driver issue, related to power states. I spent hours digging into Windows diagnostics, trying to find HP storage drivers that didn't exist, and documenting the whole thing. It was a stark reminder that even the most robust software needs a stable foundation. Thankfully, my watchdog system proved its worth by recovering Docker successfully every time, but it was still a huge distraction.

Speaking of watchdogs, I also put a lot of effort into system stability. I documented a multi-layer monitoring architecture, implemented a delayed auto-upgrade mechanism for my core services, and fixed a bunch of Docker recovery issues, especially around `SYSTEM` context limitations. And of course, having to switch Gemini models because 2.5 is getting deprecated soon was a classic maintenance headache. The RTL rendering fix for WhatsApp was a small but necessary detail for readability.

Honestly, this period felt like a mix of deep satisfaction and utter frustration. The satisfaction came from finally getting the newsletter digest right, seeing the `/ask` command work, and diagnosing that gnarly NVMe issue. The frustration was the sheer amount of time spent on infrastructure and debugging things that felt like they should just *work*. It's a constant battle between building new features and shoring up the foundations. But it's also where I learn the most – diving into OS internals, understanding AI model lifecycles, and building truly resilient systems. It feels like the hub is growing up, becoming less of a fragile prototype and more of a reliable assistant.

Next up: Automate Docker Desktop updates and keep chipping away at that NVMe driver issue.
